[2] Australia
[2a] Wolbachia mosquito release impact
Date: Fri 3 Aug 2018
Source: Daily Mail [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-6022713/Deadly-dengue-fever-wiped-entire-city-anti-virus-mosquitoes.html


Deadly dengue fever has been wiped out for the 1st time across an entire city in Australia, following the release of millions of anti-virus modified mosquitoes. Anti-dengue mosquitoes were released in Townsville, Australia in 2014. No cases have been recorded in the Queensland city, which has around 167 800 residents, since the pests' release. This is compared to 54 dengue cases between 2010 and 2014.

A total of 4 million mosquitoes were infected with Wolbachia bacteria over 2 years. The experiment started in 2014, with scientists infecting mosquitoes with Wolbachia bacteria, which prevents the insects from spreading the virus. These mosquitoes then mated with wild species, causing them to pass on Wolbachia so their offspring also carried the bacteria. This is the 1st time modified mosquitoes have wiped out such a virus across an entire city.

Dengue is not found in the UK but is in Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, South and Central America, Africa, the Pacific Islands, the Indian subcontinent, and Australia. People can reduce their risk of being bitten by dengue-carrying mosquitoes by using DEET insect repellent, wearing loose but protective clothing, and sleeping under a mosquito net.

The scheme could wipe out dengue in hard-hit countries. On the back of Townsville's success, 11 countries, including Brazil and Viet Nam, are trialing Wolbachia-infected mosquitoes.

Professor Scott O'Neill, director of the programme at Monash University, Melbourne, said: "At a cost of around [15 AUD (11 USD)] per person, the Townsville trial demonstrates the approach can be rolled out quickly, efficiently, and cost effectively to help provide communities ongoing protection from mosquito-borne diseases."

The programme aims to release Wolbachia mosquitoes in larger cities around the world with a target of reducing the cost to just 1 AUD (0.74 USD) per person. The researchers add, however, other countries that are testing the modified mosquito rollout have higher rates of dengue than Australia and therefore the scheme may not work as effectively. Despite their concerns, the scientists add results appear positive so far, the New Scientist reported.

In other research released last May [2018], it is suggested dengue fever may be passed on through sex. Scientists discovered the dengue virus in the semen of a man more than a month after he fell ill while travelling in Thailand. The virus lingering in the man's semen led researchers to believe the condition could be passed on during sex even after the other person has recovered.

The unnamed Italian man, who was in his 50s, was diagnosed with dengue fever last January [2018]. He was otherwise healthy but suffered from joint pain, fatigue and nausea. The man was admitted to the National Institute for Infectious Diseases in Rome after feeling ill for 9 days. He recovered, with traces of the virus disappearing from his blood and urine after 23 days; however, the pathogen was still present in his semen after 37 days. All traces had disappeared by day 55.

[Byline: Alexandra Thompson]

